  "body": "### Component\r\n\r\nForge\r\n\r\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\r\n\r\n- [X] Foundry\r\n- [X] Foundryup\r\n\r\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\r\n\r\nforge 0.2.0 (a44159a 2023-01-03T00:04:41.810446Z)\r\n\r\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\r\n\r\nforge fmt\r\n\r\n### Operating System\r\n\r\nmacOS (Apple Silicon)\r\n\r\n### Describe the bug\r\n\r\n`forge fmt` does not respect the `line_length` rule for this custom error definition:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\n    error SablierV2Pro__NetDepositAmountNotEqualToSegmentAmountsSum(uint128 netDepositAmount, uint128 segmentAmountsSum);\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe above has 121 lines, which is 1 line greater than the value of 120 I have set for `line_length`. If I refactor the code like this:\r\n\r\n```solidity\r\n    error SablierV2Pro__NetDepositAmountNotEqualToSegmentAmountsSum(\r\n        uint128 netDepositAmount,\r\n        uint128 segmentAmountsSum\r\n    );\r\n```\r\n\r\nRunning `forge fmt` will format the code to be like in the first code snippet, thus making Solhint throw an error.\r\n\r\n**Update**: I did some more testing and it looks like the `line_length` rule is not respected for any of the custom error definitions in my code base.\r\n\r\n### Additional context\r\n\r\nThis is my `[fmt]` configuration:\r\n\r\n```toml\r\n[fmt]\r\nbracket_spacing = true\r\nint_types = \"long\"\r\nline_length = 120\r\nmultiline_func_header = \"all\"\r\nnumber_underscore = \"thousands\"\r\nquote_style = \"double\"\r\ntab_width = 4\r\nvariable_override_spacing = false\r\nwrap_comments = true\r\n```\r\n\r\n",
